Using, $\lambda=\frac{h}{p}=\frac{h}{m v}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
&\text { So, } \frac{h}{m_p \times v_p}=\frac{h}{m_\alpha \times v_\alpha} \\
&\Rightarrow \frac{v_p}{v_\alpha}=\frac{m_\alpha}{m_p}=\frac{4 m_p}{m_p}
\end{aligned}
$$

$(\because$ mass of $\alpha$-particle is 4 times of mass of proton)
So, $\frac{v_p}{v_\alpha}=\frac{4}{1}$; i.e., $4: 1$

